Beginning with punctuation marks in the common sense, Peter Szendy goes on to trace the effects of punctuation more broadly, arguing that looking and hearing are not passive acts of reception, but themselves punctuate the images and sounds they take in. Szendy reads an astonishing range of texts and traditions, from medical auscultation to literature (Chekhov, Sterne, Kafka), philosophy (Hegel, Nietzsche, Heidegger, Derrida), psychoanalysis (Lacan), and film (Raging Bull, The Trial, Fight Club).Repeatedly, what Szendy finds in these works is a punctuation that marks experience itself, that seeks (and ultimately fails) to bind the subject to itself. This is the stigmatology of the punctuation mark on the page that structures texts from ancient to digital, as well as the punchuation of experience, as though at the hands of a boxer.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aPunctuation. 0aSigns and symbols. 0aWritten communication. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAuscultation.  aLiterature.  aPunctuation.  aStigmatology.  adeconstruction.  aexperience.  afilm.  aphilosophy.  apsychoanalysis.1 aPlug, Jan.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311072900940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823278145zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823278145423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823278145.jpg  a978-3-11-072900-9  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK